Barack Obama will be the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth US president in history.
The diploma, medal and check for 1.4 million dollars will be received, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and they will have a lot to do.
First, a visit to the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee that, in October, selected him from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
Later, the presidential couple has scheduled a meeting with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth US president to receive it, although the third to receive it in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will speak about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid such a topic, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts were further increased by sending additional troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics fail to mention.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the check for ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million CZK).
She intends to donate them for charitable purposes, but hasn&#39;t yet decided which organization.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the prime minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not fully deserving it.
Likewise, he repeated several times that the award is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he mentioned that it represents &quot;a challenge to take action.&quot;
