The &quot;Paroubek&quot; budget took money from rents and health benefits
After the left, despite the government&#39;s opinion, adds funds for farmers or civil servants, there may not be enough money in the budget for rents, health benefits or construction savings.
But neither for the interests of the state debt or international litigation.
This will harm all those who govern in the second half of next year, says Finance Minister Eduard Janota.
When the Social Democrats and Communists imposed the increase for some groups, they relied on the government to borrow later for sensitive expenses, income, or sickness benefits. &quot;That&#39;s just putting the problems off for the future, it&#39;s laying mines,&quot; says Janota.
What happens is that, when you borrow money, you have to pay higher and higher interest and, one day, you have to pay it back.
The State does not have many options to get money.
If you don&#39;t reduce social benefits or state operating expenses, you have to raise taxes.
To everyone the left added now: firefighters, teachers, farmers.
And, later, also to their children.
People don&#39;t have to worry about annuities or sickness benefits, they will receive them. Of these accounts, 1.8 billion disappeared.
But the price to pay will be the increase in public debt; next year the treasury will not only lack 163,000 million, but more.
Despite the efforts of Minister Janota, the debt will continue to increase along with interest expenses.
