USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the most intelligent man, like a diligent student repeats on the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took to be the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of Bush&#39;s Iraq script, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase &quot;same as in Iraq&quot; used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush&#39;s January 2007 statement for his own statement: &quot;A New Way Forward.&quot;
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush&#39;s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war. And that criticized it as &quot;an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.&quot;
The following months, however, showed that Bush&#39;s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, to such an extent that today nothing is said about Iraq in the news.
Bush&#39;s reputation did not improve, however objectively he left his successor with a much more favorable starting position than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander in chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subservient relationships, subjected the indecisive riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president wavered for three months, but he couldn&#39;t come up with anything better, so he at least fooled the general about 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of the entire Obama strategy seems to be his goal, to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete this procedure in three years. All of Obama&#39;s doctrine raised more questions than it offered answers.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is kept.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing their commander every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a Potemkin village. After him will remain patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated by confusing relationships, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even setting a state that is &quot;actionable,&quot; a minimal goal of the entire operation, doesn&#39;t seem very real.
The horizon of Obama&#39;s strategy is shocking due to its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now on the verge of exploding.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to &quot;come home soon&quot; will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for troop withdrawal is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect statement of US defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what relationship the security of Germany or Italy has with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have a difficult decision to make: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only bright spot for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away and therefore there is still plenty of time to find another strategy, if this one turns out to be a complete failure.
Goldman Sachs bank executives will no longer receive cash bonuses
The top executives of the US bank Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
The entity announced it to react to harsh criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 senior managers will receive, instead of money, shares that cannot be sold for a minimum period of five years.
In addition, the shares may be withdrawn in the event that they have assumed excessive risks.
According to Reuters, Goldman Sachs thus became the leader in the effort to unite bonuses on Wall Street with long-term power.
I guess Wall Street is fully aware of the longer road it has to take, said former JPMorgan investor banker Douglas Elliott.
The problem is in the details, he added.
Goldman Sachs bank faced criticism after setting aside nearly $17 billion (nearly CZK 300 billion) for bonuses in the first three quarters of this year.
The total sum of the bonuses in the entity for this year, according to the Reuters agency, probably exceeds, despite the measure announced today, 20,000 million dollars.
The high bonuses in the banking sector became, with the advent of the financial crisis, a sensitive issue in politics.
Britain announced on Wednesday that it plans to tax bonuses for bankers in excess of 25,000 pounds (approximately 712,000 CZK) at one time, with a fifty percent tax.
France is also preparing similar measures.
This year women received Nobel Prizes in all categories except Physics
Five women, which is a record number, received this year&#39;s Nobel Prizes in specialized categories and in literature from King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden today in Stockholm.
In addition to the four scientists, a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was also among the winners.
The Nobel Prize in medicine was received by two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel in chemistry was awarded to the Israeli Ada Jonath and the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for explaining the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize awarded, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was received by the American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
This prize was received today by the scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, fax machines or telescopes.
Each winner collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million SEK (approximately 25 million CZK).
In the case of having several winners in each category, the prize is divided between them.
The traditionally most anticipated Nobel, that of Peace, was received this afternoon in Oslo, Norway, by US President Barack Obama.
In his speech, he acknowledged the controversy of having been awarded, since he is at the beginning of his career and is also at the head of a country that is participating in two wars: in Iraq and in Afghanistan.
To defend his policy, however, he added that in certain situations wars are essential to achieve peace, even if their price is high.
