Mandela in the new movie by Clint Eastwood, played by Morgan Freeman
South Africans say that the new Hollywood movie, Invictus: Invincible, tells a lot about the country, its struggle and its victories, although some critics say that the leading roles are played by American actors.
The story talks about sports, race relations and Nelson Mandela.
The tireless fighter against the racist apartheid regime in the Republic of South Africa and its first black president, Nelson Mandela, is played in his biography by Oscar-winning American actor Morgan Freeman.
Freeman said Mandela, 91, asked him to play him in Eastwood&#39;s film.
Another important role is played by Matt Damon.
I told him, &quot;When I interpret for you, I&#39;ll have to have access to you.
The seventy-two-year-old actor, who received the award for his role in Eastwood&#39;s boxing drama Million Dollar Baby, played the role of the leader of the movement for the abolition of slavery, who ended up as a slave, of the fictional President of the USA, and even from God in Evan Almighty. But he rarely represented someone who is still alive and, for many people, he is as important as Mandela.
The former South African statesman spent 27 years in prison for his activities to end apartheid in the Republic of South Africa.
He was released in the year 1990 and for four years he became president of the country.
In 1993 he received the Nobel Peace Prize.
Invictus - Invincible is a Latin word and the title of a poem by the English author William Ernest Henley, published in 1875.
The challenge was to speak like him
The film is a true story about Nelson Mandela, who joined forces with the captain of the South African rugby union team, Francois Pienaar, to help unite the country. Mandela, the new president, knows that after apartheid his nation remains racially and economically divided.
He believes that he is capable of uniting his people through sport, and that is why he decides to unite rugby players, who belong to the outsiders to a world extent.
The South African team manages to reach the World Cup in 1995.
Freeman worked for several years to get Mandela&#39;s story into theaters.
He had no other goal than to play this role in such a way that it was as close to reality as possible, Freeman said.
Naturally, the biggest challenge was speaking like him.
The actor said that if he and the world politician were from the same area, he would have tried to meet Mandela, have dinner with him, go backstage before his speech.
Most importantly, he wanted to shake Mandela&#39;s hand.
I discovered that by squeezing your hand, I receive your energy, it is transmitted and I had the feeling of knowing how you feel, he said.
It&#39;s important to me to try to become a different person.
Matt Damon plays the role of François Pienaar, the captain of the national rugby team, which was dominated by white players.
The actor said he had six months to prepare for a role in the tough world of rugby union.
A big surprise for him was when he finally met Pienaar for the first time at his home.
I remember knocking on the door, he opened it and the first thing I said to François Pienaar in my life was: &quot;In the film I look much taller.&quot;
Despite the obvious differences between the actors&#39; characters and their real models, and under director Eastwood&#39;s management, Invictus: Invincible received positive reviews and talk of Oscar ambitions.
Daily Variety magazine film critic Todd McCarthy summed up his assessment with these words: &quot;It was a very good story, a very well made movie.&quot;
