If virus replication is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from VŠCHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarbonanes have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarbonanes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon, and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is unlike any drug used today, and thus may solve the problem of resistance.
In their work the scientists find new, &#39;improved&#39; compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to virus albumin.
Metallocarbonanes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteasis, cleavage of the HIV virus does not occur and mature and infectious virus corpuscles would not be created.
If we stop HIV proteasis, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient&#39;s body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV proteasis was carried out in a test tube, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from patients with HIV.
The effect of metallocarbonanes on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as on clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, where the drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the unique effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications make metallocarbonanes interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína. Řezáčová, the head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and of the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
