The pneumococcal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococcal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As the first vaccine it must be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, opinions are already appearing that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine are complete.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting the maximum prices for the vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
The experts are also already clear about the vaccination procedure.
the new vaccine
Free vaccinations for children born in August
Starting in January, children born after August 2 of last year will be able to receive the pneumococcal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is not having received a single dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and fifth month of age of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily stopped vaccinating their children against pneumococci.
The parents, however, paid for a dose 1600 crowns and more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate younger children.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns annually on vaccinations.
However, they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far the state spent for all vaccination of children approximately 500 thousand annually.
Covered vaccination was pioneered by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and sepsis.
From pneumococcal infections in our country every year, according to hospital investigations, 28 children no older than 10 years of age die.
In addition to the Czech Republic, the covered pneumococcal vaccine in children was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, at the same time opinions appear, that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
As of January it must be covered by insurance companies and voluntary.
Mandatory vaccination would be better, said Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association, for example.
His association has been promoting pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
Experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It&#39;s not entirely ideal.
On the other hand we are happy to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we now have to take, Kalovský mentioned.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At this moment we do not think about it at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary Vaccine Has Its Downsides, Doctors Say
The president of the pediatric society Odborná společnost praktických dětských lékařů Hana Cabrnochová acknowledges that the voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children would receive the vaccine, one can reason about reducing the number of doses. &quot;In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have started vaccination on a voluntary basis,&quot; says Cabrnochová.
Experts expect that from next year more than 80 percent of young parents will let their babies be vaccinated against pneumococcus.
The pneumococcal vaccine is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children it is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, in order to save later on treatment, explains Cabrnochová.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However pediatricians are concerned about the purchase of vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be bought by insurance companies and given out to doctors, just like other vaccines are given by the state.
Some deputies, however, were afraid that insurance companies could &quot;take money out of health insurance&quot;.
The doctors will therefore have to buy the vaccines and wait until they are paid for by the insurance companies.
It is estimated that pediatricians will invest 40,000 a month in vaccines, which is a remarkable sum.
It will not be easy, says Cabrnochová.
