Managerial revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our fight for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees is reminiscent of the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to certain &quot;values&quot; From above, as before, it was a matter of imposing products designed by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies to conquer markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to customer preference factors is repeat regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the company&#39;s intellectual functions, especially R&amp;D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) &quot;requires that all parties involved (...) have a proactive behavior and a prospective vision&quot;; This requires a commitment from the employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting collaborators at the center of the company&#39;s concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls are relatively useful
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, spur a managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I&#39;m afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many turns, all companies essentially end up doing... what they always did! B989
-Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic vision of human behavior.
Coming from the great schools of engineering, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory that the American &quot;neurosciences&quot; recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely disseminated behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the &quot;commands&quot; (sic) of executive commitment, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management position, unsuitable for today&#39;s world. .
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, supposes adopting a final vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects come true.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilizing factors, company managers can control, forecast and anticipate their &quot;social performance&quot; and relocate human resource management &quot;in place&quot;.
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
