the cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-tall animal that ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with claws. sickle-shaped and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been anything special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily features, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in the journal Science on Thursday.
The species lived around 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which then lay in a dry area on the supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began a dig at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes we have found as many as a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected the remains of five specimens in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name &quot;Tawa&quot; comes from the Hopi Indian sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: &quot;Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found.&quot;
Other dinosaur experts don&#39;t quite share his enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, about when the saurians divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadrupedal sauropods known as &quot;necked long&quot; and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with a bird&#39;s pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt and his colleagues&#39; analysis, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in the Tawa hallae skull, the researchers found evidence of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae also the bones of the vertebral column were evidently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers deduce that saurians first arose there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other not very closely related theropods.
All three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We think there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Naturally, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group to the dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a puzzle.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today&#39;s crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while the relationship died out at the limit of the Triassic to the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
