While awake, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts, the limits between imagination and reality vanish.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our darkened rooms with our eyes closed, we can indulge our wildest imaginations and fantasy creations without restraint.
However, someone who experiences sleep-like states while awake, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addicted, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or the drugged.
It&#39;s our imagination to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between dreams, madness, and reality.
Dream-modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neural communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been thrown off track and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts very frequently appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and dreams has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of dream in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a &quot;great similarity of the state of madness with dream states&quot;, for Sigmund Freud, the dream even it was &quot;a psychosis, with all the nonsense, crazy formations, and mirages of it.&quot;
