In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in their lives with schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent illness after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of over-arousal that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or mania. persecution.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The person affected is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centred, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the General Psychiatry Clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is in the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
That is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up is impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in their life
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, &quot;the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.&quot;
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are supported by reality, distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, it is still unknown why our brain does caprioles.
According to Fuchs, states of exception can lead anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not all people develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that there are other determining factors in addition to genes.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neural maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral illness of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system is produced, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can trigger a psychosis when there is already a previous disposition.
In the same way, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, since they interfere with the transmission system of the brain.
when the brain heats up
The illogicality of all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says professor of psychology Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our heads), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychoses, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, frequently also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer&#39;s and head injuries.
surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or underinhibited; when our brain heats up, but also when there is a lack of stimuli.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, lovesickness or other exceptional brain states.
In jüngeren Studien gab bis zu einem Drittel der Befragten an, mindestens einmal im Leben eine Halluzination erlebt zu haben.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
