She&#39;s awake and she sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the next bench.
You can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It&#39;s a nice feeling, he likes the boy.
Sometimes she wonders if she&#39;s crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and they disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class, sometimes he cannot follow the lesson because the teacher – to his eyes and ears – is introducing a new classmate, while for the rest he visibly and audibly explains the mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While she waits in the dark room for sleep to come, which is often late and scarce, she can&#39;t tell if she&#39;s awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of your open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
She hasn&#39;t told her parents and friends anything, they would think she&#39;s crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed the selectivity test last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have disappeared for a year.
Since she came into contact with the psychologist Kasten over the Internet, she knows that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of despair.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while they begin to hallucinate.
I believe that the brain is unoccupied and takes charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a child and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he found out that the man he has called dad for as long as he can remember is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noise, sufferers like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, that&#39;s why they seem so real.&quot;
Kasten also classifies nocturnal fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
Contrary to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are capable of recognizing their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises her patients to appreciate their hallucinations as a special ability.
Borderline situation between dream and hallucination
In this overly conscious-focused world, imagined experiences are often pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease, but it also contains something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person experiencing them believes to be real and cannot subsequently differentiate from being awake.
Oneiric conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische Lähmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or of the world due to total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with an imaginary world of one&#39;s own that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own ability to create allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, from Zurich, describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his consciousness embarked on journeys of several days after a heart valve operation including heart transplantation, while his body was condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen plunged into a world created by himself and visited strange places from other times: he found himself bedridden, an elderly man on board a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorbike kidnapped him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the firn snowy Alps, and ran into a Korean mobster.
He gives everything in these imaginary events, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, this is how he describes his experience.
On the contrary, the memories of the mental trips are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the internal reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Each change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist Kasten, &quot;can lead to a distortion of what we call reality.&quot;
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
