Light commercial sales rise
Almost two years later, the light commercial vehicle market is beginning to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 units that were registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, what is more important, represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decreases, according to figures from the employers&#39; association of the manufacturers Anfac and from that of Ganvam vendors.
The good data, however, should be put in quarantine since the reference with which the comparison is made - November 2008 - was particularly bad, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
The consequence of this is that, despite the rise in the last month, accumulated registrations in these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, 95,853 units have been sold, adding up all the vehicles that make up the mixed bag of light commercials: derivatives of passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, light vans and light trucks/chassis.
Likewise, the dark clouds that most affect their demand have not disappeared, because although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small and medium-sized companies, which pay in almost 100% of cases through external financing.
So, in addition to the restrictions caused by the closed faucet of bank loans, we must add other factors such as the increase in unemployment levels or the persistence of the poor economic situation.
Given this scenario and unlike passenger cars, aid for the purchase of the 2000E has been of little use.
In addition to individuals, the self-employed and SMEs that are going to purchase a light commercial vehicle of up to 3.5 tons with a level of CO2 emissions that does not exceed 160 grams per kilometer can benefit from them, but the number of operations has been testimonial.
Just yesterday, from Ganvam they once again recalled the need for the Administration to devote special attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses).
The vendors&#39; association forecasts a 2010 similar to the year just ended, for which it calculates a drop in sales (of passenger cars and 4x4s) of 19%.
Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As it happened with the anti-lock brakes ABS and will happen with the stability control ESP, the emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they already apply to all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a grace period is set for the rest until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to its way of working, it can also help to avoid many rear-end collisions.
What the emergency braking assistant does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver&#39;s stomp.
But this one doesn&#39;t always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of car components Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not hit the brakes before the collision and half of them did not use their full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance the car takes to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
