Thank you so much
After the days of wine and roses since last spring in which asset inflation has been the dominant trend in the markets, uncertainty once again reappears in the markets, which should not be surprising since it is its natural state, in an environment in which agents make decisions about the future by nature uncertain.
The medicine used by the central banks to stabilize the markets was to monetize debt with the direct purchase of assets and indirectly giving a free bar of liquidity at rates close to zero so that financial institutions could buy assets to discount.
The central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have practically ended and, without questioning their unorthodox liquidity policy, they are beginning to throw some sand into the gears like the ECB did with its year-to-year auction next week.
Therefore, investors doubt the ability of the world economy to maintain the economic recovery without such unorthodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal of the reduction in risk premia.
Stock market volatilities and corporate bond spreads have picked up again, although they are still far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
The states were forced to socialize private risk and the public debt is once again affected.
Once again there is a flight to quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the refuge chosen by investors, causing a widening of the spreads of the eurozone countries with respect to Germany.
Spain had barely been affected by this episode of instability, but Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s came along and threatened a new downward review of the rating of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, some uncertainty is not a bad thing to silence the defenders of moral hazard who were once again trying to create a conscience on those responsible for world economic policy for having stopped the destructive effects derived from the credit restriction on the destruction of employment, when what should be done is decree a new Thanksgiving day.
However, what happened in Dubai paints a tribal fight between the emirs to rebuild power in the emirates and what happened in Greece we have seen before.
A government that hides public deficit, elections and a new government that pulls the blanket.
Prodi did it in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It makes no sense that Ecofin saved Hungary from defaulting on its external payments at the beginning of the year and that it is going to allow a euro member country to default on its commitments.
What does make sense is that Ecofin has forced the Greek government to be transparent and make its citizens co-responsible for the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we expect, we find ourselves facing an episode of normalization of temporary risk premiums, after some excesses in leveraged positions, it would be within expectations.
In the Spanish case, as long as our public debt spreads widen like European corporate bonds, we should not worry.
If European spreads decrease and ours continue to widen, then it would be an idiosyncratic Spanish risk.
The Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s thing is an anecdote. When our leading indicators are forcing the majority of study services to anticipate their recovery scenarios and to revise their scenario for 2011 upwards, including the OECD and the European Commission, to return to the fray with a Japanese scenario for the Spanish economy, it is not augurs much hope of life to his warning.
Again, it looks like it will be an excellent opportunity to buy Spanish assets, although for now &quot;prudence, driver friend&quot;.
