Internet auction of damaged cars
Last October, the Solera group bought Autoonline, an internet platform for the sale of damaged cars, motorcycles or special vehicles.
The operation involved a disbursement of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company&#39;s capital, which could be expanded next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sale service is aimed exclusively at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, leasing companies, workshops, scrapyards and professional sellers who must register before starting to carry out operations.
This platform was created in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations throughout Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany.
Its main markets include Spain, Greece, Poland and Türkiye.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 experts.
3,000 daily ads are managed and about 100 new ads are included in the Spanish market every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been removed cannot be put back into circulation, but certain parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Cars with historical value can be registered even if they have been deregistered after some cumbersome procedures.
Workshop budget in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company guarantees that the user obtains a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, search for the spare part, create a quote and generate a quote.
Ease of use is an essential condition for these systems, especially to convince older professionals, who to a greater or lesser extent tend to be more reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, which are 666 passenger cars, 109 SUVs, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans, and 44 trucks.
Naturally, to use it you need a computer with an internet connection.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by means of its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and, later, the necessary spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as the price of labor, surcharges or discounts, and can then print the estimate to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an assessment tool like AudaPlus, but rather a catalog of references.
The main difference between the two systems is that the workshop-oriented one does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is 350 euros per year, which the client can finance.
The company Audatex is currently working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics welcome, as it will allow, for example, a door to be selected and turned around to see the inside.
